\begin{abstract}
We present a Hamiltonian Crystal formulation of the QCD vacuum, in which discrete Fock-space spectral gaps act as a lattice of vacuum excitations. Quarks and gluons occupy these energy levels, giving rise to hadrons, mesons, baryons, and glueballs. Explicit formulas are derived for the masses of low-lying hadrons and glueballs in terms of the vacuum spectral gaps and confinement potential. The model is Lorentz- and gauge-invariant, reproduces linear Regge trajectories, and predicts testable correlations in hadron mass spectra and potential tiny time-dependent oscillations. This framework unifies QCD vacuum structure, confinement, and the emergent particle spectrum under a quantized lattice picture.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
The nontrivial structure of the QCD vacuum is responsible for phenomena such as confinement, hadron formation, and glueball excitations. Standard treatments rely on lattice QCD simulations, instanton calculus, or effective field theory approximations. In this work, we introduce a Hamiltonian Crystal approach: the QCD vacuum is modeled as a lattice of discrete energy gaps (\(\Delta E_i\)) forming a Fock-space ladder, with quarks and gluons occupying these levels to produce observable hadrons. The framework preserves gauge invariance, Lorentz symmetry, and allows for predictive mass calculations.

\section{Hamiltonian Crystal QCD Vacuum}
We define the Hamiltonian for the vacuum and excitations:
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm vac} = H_{\rm gluon} + H_{\rm quark} + H_{\rm conf} + H_{\rm portal} + H_{\rm vac\_gaps},
\end{equation}
where
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(H_{\rm gluon}\) is the pure Yang-Mills term for gluon excitations,
    \item \(H_{\rm quark}\) contains quark mass and kinetic energy,
    \item \(H_{\rm conf} \sim \sigma r\) is the linear confinement potential,
    \item \(H_{\rm portal}\) represents weak couplings to hidden-sector Fock modes,
    \item \(H_{\rm vac\_gaps}\) encodes the discrete vacuum spectral gaps.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Fock-Space Ladder}
We assign gluon Fock-space states:
\begin{equation}
|n_g\rangle, \quad n_g = 0,1,2,\dots, N_{\rm max}, \qquad E_{n_g} = n_g \Delta E_g,
\end{equation}
and quark Fock-space states:
\begin{equation}
|n_{q_i}\rangle, \quad n_{q_i} = 0,1,2,\dots, \qquad E_{q_i} = m_{q_i} + n_{q_i} \Delta E_q.
\end{equation}

\subsection{Hadron Formation}
Hadrons arise as Fock-space combinations:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Mesons: \(|q\bar{q}\rangle = |n_q=1, n_{\bar{q}}=1, n_g=0\rangle\)
    \item Baryons: \(|qqq\rangle = |n_{q_1}=1, n_{q_2}=2, n_{q_3}=3, n_g=1\rangle\)
    \item Glueballs: \(|gg\rangle = |n_g=2, n_q=0\rangle\)
\end{itemize}

The total energy is:
\begin{equation}
E_{\rm hadron} = \sum_i E_{q_i} + \sum_j E_{n_g} + \langle V_{\rm conf} \rangle, \quad V_{\rm conf}(r) \sim \sigma r
\end{equation}

\section{Mass Spectrum Calculations}

\subsection{Glueball Masses}
For the lightest glueball (\(n_g = 2\)):
\begin{equation}
m_G \approx 2 \Delta E_g + \langle V_{\rm conf} \rangle \sim 2(0.3~{\rm GeV}) + 1~{\rm GeV} \approx 1.6~{\rm GeV},
\end{equation}
consistent with lattice QCD.

\subsection{Hadron Masses and Regge Trajectories}
Baryon masses follow:
\begin{equation}
M_B^2 \sim \sum_i \Delta E_{q_i}^2 + \sum_j \Delta E_{g_j}^2,
\end{equation}
yielding linear \(J \sim \alpha' M^2 + \alpha_0\) trajectories naturally from the Fock-space lattice.

\subsection{Time-Crystal Oscillations}
Residual spectral gaps produce small time-dependent modulations:
\begin{equation}
\Delta E(t) = \Delta E_0 + \delta \Delta E \cos(\omega t),
\end{equation}
with \(\delta \Delta E / \Delta E_0 \sim 10^{-15}\), offering a potential experimental signal in precision mass measurements.

