\section{Conclusion}
The Hamiltonian Crystal QCD vacuum provides a self-consistent, Lorentz- and gauge-invariant framework for emergent hadrons. Fock-space spectral gaps act as discrete vacuum levels hosting quarks and gluons, producing mesons, baryons, and glueballs with correct mass scales and Regge behavior. The approach is predictive and experimentally falsifiable, with potential new signals arising from ultra-small vacuum oscillations.

